        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>The only resolute, &amp; actiue, rightly wise man, pra[e]sently applieth al to himself, &amp;
                    actually appropriatith whatsoeuer worthy doings, writings, or sayings, of any other,
                    To his own pra[e]gnant vses; &amp; to [the] quicker dispatching of his particular Causes, &amp; Effects:
                    with powerable, &amp; inuincible successe.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>{ Omnis autem Polemica[e] Scientia[e], et Virtutis, ad hodierna[m] Vsque diem perfectissima Idea, Vnica
                    Ca[e]saris Militia: Opus Inco[m]parabile, et ad cuius Methodu[m] Omnia Strategemata debeant referri: cum hodierna etiam Praxi.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>But towards this very day, the most perfect archetype of all military skills and virtues, [is] the unparallelled campaign of Caesar: 
            an incomparable work, and all strategems ought to be referred to his methods: even with today's praxis.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
